951.text:
54:55
If Brandon is as biased in a single data that he announces regarding this sequence, I can't imagine the rest of the supposed factual truths that he has constantly used since the beginning of the debate.

I was curious and I fact-ckecking the " slave ships was own by Jews " assertions:

"Slave ships were mostly financed, built, and operated by European Christians. Large colonial companies such as the Royal African Company (British) or the West India Company (Dutch) were the major players. The main countries involved were Portugal (Catholics), Spain (Catholics), Great Britain (Protestant), France (Catholics), the Netherlands (Calvinists), and later the United States (Baptists, Methodists, Presbyterians, Anglicans, and Catholics).

It is historically true that some Jewish merchants, particularly Sephardim based in the Caribbean, may have been involved in the slave trade.
However, they represented only a tiny minority of the traders and shipowners involved.

Serious research, such as that of historian Eli Faber in Jews, Slaves, and the Slave Trade : Setting the Record Straight (1998), shows that Jewish participation was marginal compared to the role of major European Christian elites.

The idea that "the Jews controlled the slave trade" was popularized in the 1990s by publications such as The Secret Relationship Between Blacks and Jews , a book published by the Nation of Islam, a controversial group known for its anti-Semitic rhetoric.
This book has been widely criticized by historians for its lack of rigor, ideological bias, and selective use of data."

1715.text:
“White fatigue” is entitlement in freefall. It’s not oppression—it’s the discomfort of no longer being centered. It’s the ache that comes from realizing empathy, for some, was always conditional. What we’re witnessing isn’t about our progress; it’s about their proximity to it no longer earning them applause. Whiteness is used to authoring the terms of visibility. But now it’s being asked to witness something it can’t edit. And that’s when the fatigue begins.

This isn’t about justice—it’s about the limits of performative solidarity. The fragility of a listening ear that only listens when it’s being thanked for listening. Let’s call it what it is: white fatigue is boredom with not being praised. It’s the moment the conversation stops flattering them. When our pain stops being poetic and starts being political. When the dopamine of protest selfies fades and all that’s left is accountability. And instead of leaning in, they leave. They change the channel. They mute the thread. They say we’re “too angry” or “hard to please”—but what they mean is we stopped thanking them for doing the bare minimum.

Oppression is not discomfort. It is the systemic design of power to erase your body, distort your voice, rewrite your history, and mortgage your future. What many white Americans mistake for oppression is the ache of no longer being the gravitational center. It’s not censorship. It’s decentering. And for some, that’s unbearable—because whiteness has been taught that being centered is the same as being safe. So when that centering gets disrupted, it doesn’t feel like balance. It feels like theft.

White grievance isn’t new. It’s the mythology of dominance dressed up as victimhood. White power has never meant equality—it’s meant being the default, never needing to explain yourself because the world was already built in your image. Now, for the first time, that image is being questioned. And when accountability feels like persecution, you’re not oppressed—you’re just not used to consequence.

Look around: white teens caught on video calling Black kids slurs, then launching GoFundMe pages—and getting thousands. That’s not justice. That’s the monetization of impunity. Because white supremacy doesn’t just live in laws. It lives in algorithms. In viral sympathy. In the presumption of innocence before a single question is asked. Whiteness is the only identity that can confess to racism and still be comforted for the courage it took to say it.

What white victimhood wants is the poetry of suffering without the fire. The hashtags without the hurt. The costume of oppression without the cost. But oppression is not an aesthetic. And the center—if it is ever to hold—must finally make room for those who were never allowed to speak.

2369.text:
African Americans were growing economically (largely on their own) ever since the abolition of slavery in the late 19th century. This trend continued on into the twentieth century as well.

African Americans were predominantly concentrated in the south by the turn of the century. In 1900, 89.7% of African Americans were still living in the south. This began to fall rapidly as they moved north looking for better economic opportunity such that by 1950, it was down to 68.8%, and dropped another 8% by 1960.

African American labour force participating rates were high, and comparable to that of white Americans by the turn of the century . But African Americans saw a downward trend throughout the first half the 20th century. Africans Americans participation dropped 8 percentage points to 88.8% by 1960.

After slavery ended almost all African Americans worked in either the agriculture or service industry. This steadily declined as they diversified their supply of labour, such that by 1950, only 24.6% of males still worked in fishing, forestry or farming while 56.6% of females still worked in service. These continued to decline further.

African Americans greatly expanded their educational attainment in the decades of the 40s and 50s. Going from 8.2% to 32.2% for males and 12.5% to 36.3% for females. These were about half the percentages of whites in 1960.

In 1880, the average African American only earned 34% of the income of a white person. By 1950, this has increase such that the average African American aged 20-59 now earned 53.2% of an even greater white’s income. Which was around $3,100 in 1950.

The wealth per capita ratio of whites to African Americans was 60:1 immediately after slavery. Because they started with nothing, this fell drastically to 30:1 by 1870. By 1920, it was down to 10:1 and 30 years after that in 1950 it was 7:1. The current ratio is still 6:1.
